parameters.description: Log mortality rate for juvenile COTS (age 0-2 years), representing high early-life mortality of 80-90% annually
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log juvenile COTS mortality rate (year⁻¹), high mortality phase before maturation

parameters.description: Log mortality rate for adult COTS (age 2+ years), representing lower adult mortality of 30-50% annually consistent with 3-7 year lifespan

parameters.description: Log baseline maturation rate at reference temperature, representing transition from juvenile to adult stage. This is the rate at temp_ref_maturation, modulated by temperature via Q10_maturation

parameters.description: Log Q10 temperature coefficient for COTS maturation rate. Q10 represents the factor by which maturation rate increases per 10°C temperature increase. Typical values for ectotherm development are 2.0-3.0, with initial value of 2.5 representing moderate temperature sensitivity
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log Q10 coefficient for temperature-dependent maturation (dimensionless). Controls how strongly temperature accelerates or decelerates COTS development and sexual maturation

parameters.description: Reference temperature for baseline maturation rate. This is the temperature at which maturity_rate_base applies without temperature modification. Set near mean regional SST (~27°C for GBR)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Reference temperature for baseline COTS maturation rate (°C)

parameters.description: Optimal sea surface temperature for fast-growing Acropora coral growth. Acropora species typically have higher thermal optima than massive corals, with peak growth around 28°C on the GBR
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Optimal temperature for fast-growing coral growth rate (°C)

parameters.description: Optimal sea surface temperature for slow-growing massive coral growth. Massive corals (Porites, Faviidae) typically have slightly lower thermal optima than Acropora, with peak growth around 27°C
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Optimal temperature for slow-growing coral growth rate (°C)

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity parameter for fast-growing coral growth when temperature is BELOW optimal. Controls the width of the thermal performance curve on the cool side. Moderate sensitivity as cooling is less damaging than warming for corals
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of fast coral growth to cooling below optimum (°C⁻²), moderate impact

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity parameter for fast-growing coral growth when temperature is AT OR ABOVE optimal. Controls steepness of decline during thermal stress. Acropora are highly vulnerable to bleaching, so this should be higher (steeper decline) than cooling sensitivity. Higher values mean growth declines more rapidly with warming
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of fast coral growth to warming above optimum (°C⁻²), high vulnerability to heat stress

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity parameter for slow-growing coral growth when temperature is BELOW optimal. Controls the width of the thermal performance curve on the cool side. Moderate sensitivity as cooling is less damaging than warming
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of slow coral growth to cooling below optimum (°C⁻²), moderate impact

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity parameter for slow-growing coral growth when temperature is AT OR ABOVE optimal. Massive corals (Porites, Faviidae) are more thermally tolerant and bleach-resistant than Acropora, so this should be LOWER (gentler decline) than fast_warm sensitivity, creating a broader thermal tolerance. Lower values mean growth declines more gradually with warming
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of slow coral growth to warming above optimum (°C⁻²), lower vulnerability to heat stress than fast corals

parameters.description: Log maximum recruitment rate for fast-growing Acropora corals. Acropora are opportunistic colonizers with high reproductive output and rapid larval settlement. Typical recruitment rates range from 0.1-1.0 year⁻¹ under favorable conditions
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log maximum recruitment rate for fast-growing corals under optimal conditions (year⁻¹), representing opportunistic colonization strategy

parameters.description: Log maximum recruitment rate for slow-growing massive corals (Porites, Faviidae). These corals have lower reproductive output and slower recruitment than Acropora, typically 0.05-0.3 year⁻¹, reflecting a persistent rather than opportunistic strategy
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log maximum recruitment rate for slow-growing corals under optimal conditions (year⁻¹), representing persistent colonization strategy

parameters.description: Optimal temperature for fast coral larval settlement and early survival. Acropora larvae settle optimally at slightly cooler temperatures than adult growth optimum, typically during spring/early summer spawning periods on GBR (27-28°C)
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Optimal SST for fast coral larval settlement success (°C)

parameters.description: Optimal temperature for slow coral larval settlement and early survival. Massive corals have broader thermal tolerance and slightly lower settlement optima than Acropora, around 26-27°C
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Optimal SST for slow coral larval settlement success (°C)

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity of fast coral larval settlement. Acropora larvae are sensitive to temperature extremes, with narrow thermal windows for successful settlement. Higher sensitivity (steeper decline away from optimum) than slow corals
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of fast coral larval settlement (°C⁻²), narrow thermal tolerance window

parameters.description: Log thermal sensitivity of slow coral larval settlement. Massive coral larvae have broader thermal tolerance than Acropora, with gentler decline in settlement success away from optimum temperature
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log thermal sensitivity of slow coral larval settlement (°C⁻²), broader thermal tolerance window than fast corals

parameters.description: Log Allee threshold for fast coral recruitment. Below this cover level, recruitment is reduced due to limited larval production and fertilization success. Fast corals show stronger Allee effects than slow corals. Threshold around 1-5% cover
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log Allee threshold for fast coral recruitment (% cover), below which recruitment is impaired

parameters.description: Log Allee threshold for slow coral recruitment. Massive corals show weaker Allee effects than Acropora due to longer reproductive lifespan and persistent larval production. Threshold around 0.5-2% cover
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log Allee threshold for slow coral recruitment (% cover), weaker effect than fast corals

parameters.description: Log space limitation parameter for fast coral recruitment. At high cover, recruitment saturates due to space competition and reduced settlement substrate. Fast corals show stronger space limitation than slow corals. Saturation around 20-40% cover
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log space limitation parameter for fast coral recruitment (% cover), controls saturation at high density

parameters.description: Log space limitation parameter for slow coral recruitment. Massive corals can recruit at higher densities than Acropora due to smaller colony sizes and different growth forms. Saturation around 15-25% cover
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log space limitation parameter for slow coral recruitment (% cover), weaker saturation than fast corals
